\begin{abstract}
Tree death is a fundamental process driving population dynamics, nutrient cycling, and evolution within plant communities. While past research has identified factors influencing tree mortality across a variety of scales -- including an individual's past growth, species-level functional traits, and temporal plot-scale effects; these distinct drivers are yet to be integrated within a cohesive and predictive framework. Here we apply classic survival analysis techniques within a cross-validated hierarchical Bayesian framework to derive instantaneous mortality functions that integrate individual, species, and temporal effects for 203 tropical rain forest tree species at Barro Colorado Island (BCI) Panama. We show that mortality models that separate growth-dependent and growth-independent components, use stem diameter growth rather than basal-area growth, and attribute the effect of wood density to growth-independent death, outperform alternative formulations. Moreover, we show that the effects of wood density -- a prominent trait known to influence tree mortality -- explains only a small proportion of the total variability in species mortality rates, and that temporal variation in mortality was large.  Our analysis also suggests that growth-dependent processes -- and thus competition -- predominate as the biggest driver of mortality at BCI. Combined, this study provides a framework for predicting individual-level mortality in highly diverse tropical forests, but also highlights how little we now about the causes of species-level and temporal plot-scale effects, needed to effectively predict tree mortality.
\end{abstract}

