In this study, we reconcile both intraspecific and interspecific drivers of instantaneous mortality by developing a unified model that incorporates individual-level, species-level, and temporal effects, within a cross-validated Bayesian framework. To derive this unified model, we compare the predictive accuracy of three alternative cumulative hazard functions ($\lambda_i(t)$; Fig. \ref{fig1}B) in predicting patterns of tropical tree mortality in 203 tropical rainforest trees at Barro Colorado Island (BCI), Panama. The simplest model (Fig. \ref{fig1}B, left), assumes a single baseline hazard, which is constant irrespective of a plant's growth rate. The second model (Fig. \ref{fig1}B, middle) describes a growth-dependent hazard which assumes the risk of dying eventually declines to zero as growth increases. 

Following past work \cite[e.g.][]{Kobe:1995tw, Wyckoff:2000un, Kunstler:2005bn, Vieilledent:2010fv}, we assume the growth-mortality relationship is adequately captured by a negative exponential curve, with mortality decaying exponentially until an asymptote at zero is reached. The third model (eq. Fig. \ref{fig1}B, right) is the summation of the two previous models. Specifically, this model allows $\lambda_i(t)$ to decrease exponentially with increasing growth rate, but, unlike a standard negative exponential, will asymptote at some baseline hazard instead of zero. The advantage of this model is that it effectively accounts for two independent causes of mortality: death due to growth and death due to chance (i.e. stochastic events such as wind throw and fire). Combined, these three models capture a variety of functional responses previously proposed, including effects represented in current vegetation models (Moorcroft 2001; McDowell et al 2011). However, these alternative models have not previously been systematically compared.

In deriving the unified model, we address the following specific questions:
\begin{enumerate}\itemsep 0pt
  \item Does a mortality function including both growth-dependent and independent terms outperform a model including only one of these?
  \item Which growth measure (diameter increment growth or area growth) best captures growth-dependent mortality?
  \item Does including wood density improve model predictive capacity, and if so, does it predominately affect baseline hazard, growth-dependent hazard or both?
  \item What is the proportion of inter-specific variability explained by wood density?
  \item What is the proportion of total variability explained by species, census, baseline hazard and growth-dependent hazard?
  \item Does mortality vary substantially between censuses?
\end{enumerate}
Answering these questions involves comparing predictive accuracy of alternative models. To achieve this, we used K-fold cross-validation (Fig. \ref{fig1}D). Cross-validation is a typical approach to model evaluation, and assesses a model’s accuracy when extrapolating to data not used in model calibration, thereby indicating the model’s true predictive accuracy \cite{Hooten:2015, Stone:1997tg}. Evaluating models in this way is computationally expensive, making it virtually impossible to run all combinations. For example, some of our models took over a two weeks to complete. We therefore fit models across five iterative stages of model fitting and comparison, corresponding to the six questions evaluated above, and gradually increasing model complexity (see methods).

\section*{Results}

\subsection*{Mortality strongly varies over time}
Tree mortality progressively decreased over time. Between 1995 and 2010, the highest proportion of trees death occured between 1995\textendash 2000 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique, 1)}\%) followed by 2000\textendash 2005 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique, 2)}\%) and lastly 2005\textendash 2010 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_model_dataset_true_unique, 3)}\%). Consequently, when we allowed hazard rates to be scaled by census (i.e. adding term $\delta$) we observed a significant increase in predictive accuracy (i.e. lower logarithmic loss; Fig. \ref{fig2}A). Assuming the long-term average census effect ($\delta$) is 1, then our model predicted deaths were \Sexpr{census_effects(final_model,1)}\% higher in 1995\textendash 2000, and \Sexpr{census_effects(final_model,2)}\% and \Sexpr{census_effects(final_model,3)}\% lower in 2000\textendash 2005 and 2005\textendash 2010, respectively.

