\subsection*{Effect of wood density on mortality rates}
The inclusion of wood density on either baseline or growth-dependent parameters significantly improved model accuracy relative to a hazard function without such effects (Fig. \ref{fig2} A,B). The most parsimonious combination that provided the largest gain in predictive accuracy (i.e. lowest logarithmic loss) occurred when only the baseline hazard term ($\gamma$) was varied as a function of species wood density ($\rho$; Fig. \ref{fig2} B). We found that wood density was negatively correlated with species baseline mortality rate (Fig. \ref{fig3}). This meant that species with low wood density and fast individual growths had on average higher mortality rates ((Fig. \ref{fig4} A,B), and thus higher annual probability of death (Fig. \ref{fig4} C,D), relative to high wood density species. While, wood density did improve model accuracy it only accounted for \Sexpr{pred_gain_wd(logloss_summaries)}\% of the total gain in predictive capacity that could be obtained by accounting for species differences.

\subsection*{Proportion of variation explained}
Approximately \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('species'))}\% of variation in predicted mortality rates captured by our model was due to species differences, \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('wood_density'))}\% of which was captured by wood density. Census effects accounted for approximately \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('census'))}\% of the total predicted variation in mortality rates.
As expected, the growth-dependent hazard terms (i.e. the part of the model allowed to vary by individual growth) accounted for \Sexpr{extract_prop_explained(param_variance_explained, I('growth_dependent'))}\% of the overall variation in mortality rates.

