\subsection*{Mortality rates, maximum species size and species light requirements}
We found that both $\alpha$, the effect of low growth rate, and $\gamma$, the baseline hazard term, were positively correlated with gap index (our measure of species light requirement; Fig. \ref{fig6} A,C, E). By contrast, $\beta$ (the parameter that defines the exponential decay with increasing growth rate) was negatively correlated gap index. The combination of these correlations suggest that species which predominately recruit in gaps (i.e. higher gap index) were more prone to death due to both low growth and stochastic chance. They also required faster growth rates to achieve a given mortality rate relative to a species that recruits in non-gaps. We detected no strong correlations between estimated species parameters and their associated maximum DBH (Fig. \ref{fig6} B,D,F,H).


