The underestimation of inter-specific variation suggests that there are other species attributes besides wood density that affect tree mortality rates. It has been suggested that a species light demand and maximum size are two major axes of inter-specific variation in tropical rainforests\cite{Poorter:2006tq}. While we did not explicitly model mortality as a function of these traits, our posthoc correlations  \ref{fig6} revealed that some inter-specific variation was indeed correlated with light demand. Specifically, we found that light demanding species (i.e. those with high gap index) were more susceptible to death due to both low growth and stochastic chance and required faster growth rates to achieve a given mortality rate relative to a species that readily recruits in shaded conditions, supporting findings by others\cite{Ruger:2011cv}. By contrast, we detected no correlations between a species maximum stem diameter and mortality rates, supporting findings by others\cite{Wright:2010fl}.

We recommend research should focus on examining how other traits influence growth-dependent and growth-independent hazards and what combination of traits minimises unexplained species variability. Researchers, however, should be mindful that the inclusion of additional traits comes at the cost of added complexity, increased uncertainty (i.e. more parameters to estimate) and increased minimum knowledge; all of which diminish the interpretability of models, but also the applicability of predicting mortality rates in many data poor ecosystems. Because of this, we also recommend future research focus on developing more integrative correlates of plant mortality. For example, we may have captured more inter-specific variability in baseline hazards had we used a integrative measure of plant durability such as a trait that incorporates both wood density and stem architecture.

Future research should also focus on examining how climate variables influence both growth-depedent and growth-independent hazards, particularly as climate-driven mortality is increasing globally\cite{vanMantgem:2009bi, Mcdowell:2013wf}. Our analyses revealed a significant decline in mortality at BCI between 1995 and 2010. Unfortuantely, we were unable to statistically attribute this temporal change to particular climatic variables due to low temporal replication (N=3). However, the high numbers of deaths that occurred 1995 and 2000, were likely the product of a severe drought caused by a El-Nino in 1997\textendash 1998. Droughts are known to have significant impacts on tree mortality rates in these ecosystems\cite{Condit:1995wl, Mcdowell:2013wf} Furthermore, future research should also examine how different growth measures influence predictive accuracy of mortality models. We have no clear explanation as to why DBH growth outperformed basal area growth in terms of model predictive accuracy, and we are unsure how other common measures such as biomass growth\cite{Chave:2005hz} will compare. 

Here we showcase a new framework for modelling tropical tree mortality that attempts to unifies empirical evidence from within and between species studies. This framework also provides an approach for partitioning mortality rates into growth-dependent and growth-independent hazards. Our findings reveal that while wood density is an important trait affecting mortality rates, we are still only capturing a fraction of the overall species variability in mortality rates.


